external_knowledge:
; Active experiments imply that the status of the experiment is 'active', indicating the experiment is currently in progress; 
; An agent is an entity that performs actions within an experiment, and having at least 10 agents suggests a certain level of complexity or scale in the experiment; 
; The action space being discrete refers to actions that can only take on specific, distinct values rather than any value within a continuous range; 
; Tags are labels or keywords attached to experiments for categorization or filtering purposes, and having at least 5 distinct tags indicates the experiment is well-categorized; 
; Researcher accesses refer to instances of researchers viewing, interacting with, or manipulating the experiment, and more than 10 accesses by researchers suggest significant engagement or interest in the experiment.

; Agent performance is typically measured by its ability to maximize rewards in a given environment; 
; The action and observation spaces are critical in understanding the agent's capabilities and limitations; 
; The experiment context provides valuable information about the conditions under which the agent is operating.

- Performance of an agent is determined by its average reward and maximum observation value; 
- The ranking of agents within an experiment and globally is based on their average rewards in descending order; 
- The total number of agents in each experiment is calculated by counting the distinct agent IDs within each experiment; 
- The average reward of the preceding agent is determined by the agent's position in the ordered list of agents within an experiment.

- "Most active users" refers to users with the highest total access counts; 
- An "active" experiment is one with the status 'active'; 
- A "paused" experiment is one with the status 'paused'; 
- A "completed" experiment is one with the status 'completed'; 
- "Edit operations" refer to accesses with the type 'edit'.
